"tracking a person's donation is really no time to do, because so many people donate every day. "

Thinking, Wuhan Red Cross temporary volunteers, telephone group

As of January 25, the Red Cross Society of China has received a total of 340 million yuan in charitable donations and 274 million yuan in donations. It has allocated 12.4588 million yuan worth of supplies and 10 million yuan in cash to the more serious areas such as Wuhan. [1] Wuhan Red Cross was one of five institutions designated by Hubei Province to receive donations after the outbreak.

Now we are divided into a telephone service group and a material service group. There are about 40 or 50 people in the telephone service group. The Material Service Group should also be about 50 or 60 people. The manpower of the entire Wuhan Red Cross Society is put here, and it is about this many people, 24-hour shifts.

Basically the past is training, after training began to answer the phone, materials and donations can be accepted. Tell them how to donate, where to donate, and what standards they need to meet. Tracking a person's donations is really no time to do, because so many people donate every day, I may not receive 100 calls a day, really do not have the energy to do this tracking. Some of the standard numbers are very long, and they're given to him, and they need to be written down on paper and pen, and then they need to check with him that they're correct, and that's going to be a bit of a problem, and it's going to take a little bit longer. We're on landlines. There's no way to send a text to their cell phones.

Now I work in front of several landlines. If I don't have a computer to use, I will have a form written down every day, such as the contact person, the name of the contact person, and then the problems that need to be solved, the feedback, some remarks and so on, they're assembled at the end of each shift.

The material group is mainly responsible for carrying, transporting some materials to the Red Cross, and there will be some volunteer convoys to help transport these materials. Small donations go to the Red Cross, large donations go to our logistics site, one of which has been overrun. After receiving the donation, it is handed over to the Health Commission, which has a command center here to distribute it uniformly to all the hospitals. Another is targeted donation. If the donor over there asks for a specific donation to some hospitals, for example, some will donate to mount thor and Mount Vulcan hospitals, it is to inform the hospital people to come, pick it up at the Red Cross or the warehouse.

There are some questions about targeted giving. Directional donation, it is necessary to contact the hospital, but also need to write a letter of intent to donate, provide hospital contact person, hospital open letter can be directed to receive. To make a targeted donation, first of all, you need to have three certificates for medical devices. The letter of intent for donation needs to include the manufacturer, brand, variety, specifications, quantity and value of the donation, medical device certificate is a copy or electronic version, go through these procedures, to determine whether this is valid or meet the application standards of the product, can be directly to the hospital. Then along with the express delivery, put it in, say, the express box to donate it. According to the targeted donation book to indicate the donated hospital, we will contact the hospital, the hospital opened a hospital official letter, can prove that he is a hospital, come to collect it.

If there is no letter of intent for this targeted donation, it will be uniformly distributed by the Health Commission. The committee looks at the materials to see if they are up to code, and if they fall short, they may be distributed to communities or residents.

I answer the phone myself every day, and basically work for eight hours to eight and a half hours without a break. If it is an ordinary donation, it may take about one minute, and if it is a donation of materials, it may take two to three minutes. Some will donate medical equipment, and some will donate overseas. That may take longer. It may take five to ten minutes, others, such as a targeted donation, because to tell him what materials need to be provided, the time will be longer.

Not all of the people who called were necessarily donating money or medical supplies. There were also many who wanted to donate vegetables, fruits and melons. Today, I also received a donation of strawberries, and then there was a donation of rice. There are many friends from other places who want to come and volunteer. Even today, a Beijing motorcade said that he has more than 100 cars and wants to come and help with transportation. But we don't accept these volunteers from other places for the time being. There are also some overseas donations we did not know how to deal with at first, because the Wuhan Red Cross Society Can Not Accept Overseas donations, now we let them contact the Charity Federation.

Isn't there a control system for private cars here in Wuhan? Private car owners who receive text messages are not allowed to go on the road. In fact, a fleet of private cars still exists. The private cars that won't let you on the road have been to the hospital recently. The owners of these private cars will receive a text message. The owners of private cars that don't receive a text message can all be on the road. It's not a one-size-fits-all kind of thing, as is rumored.

Recently there are a lot of rumors that we charge fees, in fact, we are free, their own personal contribution to the car fuel, here is to serve a meal to volunteers, the rest are free of charge obligations. I think people on the Internet are too idle to spread rumors. Because we didn't even know where the rumor came from. After there was a rumor that day, immediately a reporter from the Changjiang daily came to interview us and immediately refuted the rumor. That's actually the angriest thing I've been doing at work.

For the Red Cross overall operating efficiency is relatively low query, now everyone in the New Year, many mask factory did not start, many logistics did not start, may choose some logistics have not sent to Wuhan, this is one; Secondly, masks, AH, these medical supplies are all disposable, and the consumption is very large. It may be consumed on the same day, and it may not be enough for the consumption of the same day. Such a situation may occur.

Our distribution is all very timely. After our previous, uh, Sinopharm holding logistics warehouse was full, we have now opened a new logistics warehouse, and then some small pieces were sent out to our Red Cross Society in a very timely manner, it's probably only at night that some of this stuff gets piled up.

Logistics warehouse there is a special person to take charge, our side is mainly responsible for the front end, that is, to receive advice. I can't see where it's going, it's all back-end stuff; I can't see hospital needs, there's a list of things that are in short supply, and we'll talk to the donors about their specs.

We have a temporary fever situation of volunteers here. Before, masks might be given out once a day. Now, they will be sterilized regularly. I have sterilized my class about three times today. I have taken my temperature regularly, and a mask every two or three hours. That's the change. I think now is good, everyone is very enthusiastic, the idea is very good, whether the donors or the current operating system is slowly improving, feel quite good.

"They have their layout, but we can only see the first line"

Lou Fei, Wu da Mba Alumni Association material donation group, donation group

The MBA volunteer group at Wuhan University currently has more than 300 members. As of 2:00 pm on January 27, we have confirmed the official donation with 13 caring organizations and individuals, including over 60,000 masks, over 5,000 pairs of goggles and over 1,000 sets of protective clothing.

The Donation Organization of the Alumni Association of Wuhan University was organized by one of the alumni of Wuhan University on the 30th day of the Lunar New Year. At that time, there were only a few people around them in the group. Later, more people came in, about 200 people, the message will be very fast, basically in the send a message for help.

Because the information was so cluttered, it took some organization to organize the work flow, so four groups were formed at once. The donor group is in charge of collecting information about the donors; the second group is the recipient group, and all of these requests for help, are going to check with them, ask them for a job certificate, go online and find out if they're still working at the hospital.

After the team counts up the information, it quickly matches the hospital, contacts the volunteers to donate, and achieves such a docking effect; and the third is the transport team, where some supplies are brought in by car or chartered car from elsewhere, but they can not enter the city, the organization will contact the vehicles in Wuhan, take their goods, transport to the designated hospital, or we have verified the hospital. Then there is another group that belongs to overseas, because there is almost no domestic material that can meet the standards, and isn't the government involved already requisitioned? They look overseas to see if anything is available or up to standard, and figure out a way to deal with the situation.

At the beginning of the docking were several major fixed-point hospitals in Wuhan. Also, all donated materials were first put on the side of the Red Cross. Later, we discovered that the materials put on the side of the Red Cross, a lot of them can't be delivered directly to the doctor. We're in a hurry, too. Because we have contacted the hospital, to verify what there is lack of supplies before the Red Cross side, but all aspects of the whole process approved, there is not much way to get to the doctors in a timely manner. Doctors have been reporting that no supplies have been received and that there is nothing left to use, and that is one such situation. We're just GONNA have to figure out a way to hand it to them one-on-one, so they can use it.

Over the past two days, the government has gradually requisitioned domestic mask factories and the like, so many resources are slowly, and are being diverted to the city of Wuhan. We have also received information that, other cities outside of Wuhan, including Huanggang or Jingmen, are in short supply.

In particular, the health clinics in the villages and towns don't have anything to use at all, or even that kind of safety and hygiene cap, and then they can only use bags; they don't have, not to mention the N95 or the surgical mask, or even the health mask, they don't have any, protective clothing and goggles they, especially goggles, they never had one from the beginning. These people are in direct contact with suspected or confirmed patients, and their protection is very tight. Well, our main focus now is to find a way to get to them, and the transportation in Wuhan will stop for a while. There has been a change in our donation target,

Probably from the night before last, we had a meeting at 12 o'clock in the evening. One was that the road was closed and could not be transported at all. The other was that all aspects of the materials were gradually being tilted towards the city. Only then did we discuss and say that we would send them to places outside Wuhan.

When someone on my side wants to donate, or when the recipient group says a particular hospital is short, how much is missing, I try to organize donors. Will pull a group directly to the hospital demand side, such as nurses and so on, list the materials they need. There's GonNa be a direct contact at the hospital, our donors, the staff of the donor and recipient groups, basically. The group will issue the medical staff's work certificate, which we have verified before, but the hospital's butt hair is primarily the responsibility of the donor.

Since last night, it has been almost a form of peer-to-peer, a hospital pulling a group. Is constantly being optimized, because information is being updated so quickly, and material needs are now being donated by many organizations, not just our own. So it may need to be updated every half-day, such as the morning to say what materials needed, by noon will not be needed, or need again.

There are three hospitals in Huanggang, which I deal with directly, and one in Xiaogan, which is now joined by a town health centre. They are all currently in short supply. For example, some towns have to go to the homes of some diagnosed patients to sterilize them and so on. There is no guarantee. At most, there is a health mask at most, or better yet, wear a surgical mask, which is basically unprotected. In fact, doctors at several hospitals in Wuhan are still short of supplies because they do not receive government supplies in a timely manner. Let alone some outside Wuhan, it is almost impossible to get these. Like today in a group, we got a message that there were 500 suits on it, and they said they were told there were only 100, and they were going to send them to other hospitals in town.

For example, there is a small town hospital, is a mental hospital, there is also a confirmed case of patients, but do not cooperate with treatment and do not accept isolation. Once the hospital was diagnosed, the staff didn't have anything, their needs were minimal, 20 goggles, 21 suits, all the same, the numbers were very small, but they didn't have, in these cases, we make it a priority to get them there first. For example, yesterday, a donation organization from Henan wanted to donate 40 disinfection lamps. We contacted some small hospitals outside Wuhan. There were no disinfection lamps there. Medical staff had to carry dozens of catties of disinfection water to sterilize, we made it a priority to send it to them first. The rest of the place is missing, so we'll have to register it again.

The alcohol was so bad, there was almost no way to get it to them. Let's just say it's a little hard to buy 84. They don't really have anything to use right now, except to donate 84 sterile effervescent tablets to send them in case of emergency. They all are now, as long as they have it, because they have nothing now. As long as it is a national qualification of some manufacturers out, in line with the specifications and standards, this has been ignored.

You can't say that everything is very standard. There is no way, too late, we now group inside 28 staff are 24-hour shift, and then there is a worker, the work intensity is very big, keep in contact, but also no time to eat, have a fever. He was in Wuhan, on their own in the home self-isolation, and later really is our general manager, see he is really bad, just forced him to rest.

Freight basically can only send Shunfeng, there is a problem is the speed will be slower. SF & FUNG can not go green channel now, green channel only for the government, there are some charities and so on. Ordinary people donated, some from the Taobao order or some Shun Feng, any shipment they can only use the ordinary speed to Wuhan that way.

We do not docking manufacturers, docking is the donor, and do not accept any donations, also try not to contact their channels. Because they're sensitive, especially when it comes to donations. For example, there are some people who do wechat business, or do Daigou, in the name of the donor is in the group to contact some manufacturers, in the name of the donor to buy a large number of masks, and in our group to buy high prices. This is the two days we found a relatively bad, like some bad circumstances on the reservation of evidence to the police. If the material is up to standard and the price is right, now everyone knows that the price is basically transparent, what kind of price is reasonable? Everyone will think that this is a non-selfish supply of a channel.

Now we find that there are fewer and fewer groups, and most of them are still in the form of individuals. And individual donors are doing everything they can. Yesterday or the day before yesterday, there was a donor who placed an order, and he said, I have a limit on my spending. I'm working really hard on this, but we all have our limits.

One of the things we want to do, is if they want to give this love, they have to have a sense of trust, and the hospital that they want to verify is actually receiving their supplies. It would be sad if they paid for it and couldn't use it there. Individual volunteers do this for most of the day, constantly checking messages to see what's going on. And they'll be begging. That's what they say. I'll go begging again, see if there's anyone else I can help.

Medical supplies in the country are almost gone, depleted. Coupled with the New Year workers have gone home, the factory inside the production of this problem is difficult to solve. Many of the workers are migrant workers. They were already in their hometown before this issue came out. There was a great shortage of workers. They could not do it at all and could not return to work at once. And now there are some places that are closed, cars that can't go. The workers didn't, and transportation was a big problem.

Originally some folk, some citizens'voluntary organizations could receive the goods, but now they can not, because they do not have a pass. We've had this problem before, where our delivery vehicles, or other civilian volunteers'delivery vehicles, arrive at the hospital gate, and they can't get in, they can't get in. Now many people say they want to donate. They ask the courier companies what they can do. They say that you can donate to a local charity or the Red Cross. They have opened a special green channel to reinforce Wuhan, but only between local governments and the Red Cross. There is also a situation in Huanggang where outside donations can not be accepted. But they needed it, so we had to send it to the doctor in small pieces.

I have no prejudice against the government, the Red Cross in all its aspects, and their processes, but they may have some considerations about the overall situation. Just to say that what we are doing now is to see a situation where there is a serious shortage of medical personnel on the front line. We just want to help them more without causing trouble to the country. But the biggest problem is that it may not be able to substantially solve the problem of these health care workers all of a sudden, because the coverage is larger. They have their layout, but we can only see the first line; what they can see is different from what we can see. We can only see the first line doctors wearing plastic bags to work, unable to sleep and having no time to eat.

"We do not want to be led by others, to promote the use of a platform for Public Welfare"

Tai Ge, project manager / Volunteer, Hubei Medical Materials Demand Information Platform

Small Program "Hubei Medical Materials Demand Information Platform" launched at 10:36 am on the 25th, divided into two categories, hospital demand, vehicle resources, the collection of hospital social help and civil logistics information. More than 600 hospitals and health centres have been registered and version 4.0 is being updated. [2]

(January 24) , we see a lot of doctors, nurses lack of supplies, may not have protection on the first-line care. On the same day, many hospitals in Wuhan were in need of supplies. Then, everyone didn't have a platform to understand exactly which hospitals, what was missing and how much was missing. We just wanted to make these public to everyone, put the most pressing needs at the top of the list so you can see them.

The epidemic has obviously become very serious later in the day, but there may be many people watching the Spring Festival gala, everyone may not have paid attention to this matter. We just wanted to talk about what we could do on our own, and we didn't know what we could do.

I'm also a project manager for an Internet company myself, so the project manager for the whole platform, we're twenty people. It was a bit of a mix-up before, with everyone spontaneously developing the front end and back end. When I looked, some of the requirements were not clearly articulated. So I made a plan, and I put the team together, from the plan to the launch. We also have to input information from the back end, and there are two windows on the front end, which can be opened to hospitals and motorcades, and they can register themselves, and then we do the audit.

From just a few people at the beginning, to hundreds now. There are responsible for the verification of the hospital, and responsible for information input, as well as in charge of material docking, the hospital needs carding, material tracking. Then some people found out that it was not up to standard, so we asked some doctors and volunteers to help us examine the goods.

(platform information now) is to need to review, because (released so far) has been three or four days, the early team may be relatively pure, later found that big, there may be some not-so-pure things in it. There's GonNa be some kind of doctor impersonating a doctor, taking supplies. Now there's a hospital announcement on every major platform, and then there's a contact (information) on it, (someone) might change it to himself. (the supplies were docked) and took the goods away. In addition, there are still some vehicle information that may be incorrect and delay everyone's business, so we will approve it in advance, and then give him approval after approval,

We are currently on version 3.0 as of today (28th) , which is equivalent to a version we launch every night. The first night, we worked on it all night. It was exhausting. The next day, I'll put together a plan for this place, and it'll be up and running around 12:30. What we do now is agile iterative development, where we quickly gather requirements, quickly do development, and then go online. Because right now this platform is very time-sensitive, if we are slow, it may not be very useful.

We had a lot of help from a lot of teams. We didn't have a build-it-yourself tool, so we had worktiles that gave us a year for free. After the launch, there are also tencent news, Nandu weekly, and a lot of Weibo big V, the kind of three million fans, are willing to put the platform online publicity.

After retweeting, a lot of people may know something through this information. About the day before yesterday (26th, 27th) , the resources of many hospitals in Wuhan have already been solved. Now there is actually no shortage in Wuhan. What is in short supply is the second-tier cities and some places around Wuhan.

The first step in identifying the source of a material need is to check it against the official website to ensure a authenticity. There may be some county hospitals that don't have the time to make an announcement, there may not be an official external channel, there may be no understanding of the Internet at all, and they may not even be able to fix the pictures. In that case, we'll have them print out a requisition form, stamp it with their hospital's seal. Another way is that we would approve their doctors, and we would accept their ID and ID, and then we would send them out.

We have about four large teams doing information gathering and vetting. Including, the Wuhan University Alumni Association and the Huake Alumni Association, as well as university teachers in the North Qing Dynasty also participated in this, this information collection. The verification effort is so extensive that each volunteer may be able to verify as few as a dozen hospitals a day.

Once the information is gathered, we'll sort it. For example, when a very urgent need comes up, we'll put it in the front of the list, so that the click through rate will be higher and the attention will be more. In order of priority, because there are so many volunteers in Wuhan, the Red Cross Society on the government side, the Hubei Provincial Charity General Association, will give priority to limited supply in Wuhan. Therefore, the current very scarce words may be the periphery. Priority is given to designated hospitals, and if there is still a surplus under the premise of meeting designated hospitals, then such hospitals with more patients receiving fever treatment will be met. We are also aware of the staffing of some hospital departments and will adjust their priorities accordingly.

We (this platform) went out, found that there will be some false information in the inside, so we (28) the evening of the temporary emergency off-line, ready to approve and then on-line. After the line, there are some county hospital staff, ran to ask how the hospital suddenly off-line. Because after the platform disappeared, no one went to receive donations to their hospital anymore, so maybe at first you didn't feel how useful the platform seemed. Later, after today's emergency, i found that if these hospitals were taken offline, it would still have a huge impact on them,

So far we have three new iterations, the first version is a lot of Wuhan city designated large hospitals, later found that they are full, we will put it down. On the second iteration, there are about 400 or 500 today, with more to come.

In the first version, it was probably just about the needs of the hospital. The next day, we found that volunteers can find hospital docking, but logistics information is particularly difficult to find a convoy to send them in. Then we quickly discussed the requirements, and the vehicle information must also be registered. Otherwise, we could not find a vehicle to deliver the goods to the hospital, so we included the vehicle fleet in the second version, we also have an information exchange approval group for the convoy.

The platform was hacked once the next day after it was launched, maliciously altering the domain name. We were afraid that someone would use it to hack into the data. We did back-office security again, which is why there's an announcement that says "official certification, " but it's not with the government. We're a neutral team, and at this point in time, we're just trying to do something useful to help people.

We are not willing to be led by others, that is, to be pushed to become a platform for public welfare, which is not called public welfare, that is to say, our own purpose is to publish such information about the hospitals and vehicles we have approved, and after seeking some media or micro-blogs in place to publicize such information, everyone knows that this matter can be used to the information on this platform. They can either be the donors or the demanders of the city hospitals. They can accomplish what they are, for example, the donors can feel at ease, to be able to contact the hospital to contact the vehicle to donate his things, the hospital to be able to address his material needs, these two things.

We must regulate ourselves. We have to accept the public's demand for open information and transparency, and then we have to accept public scrutiny, and I have to do that well.

Why didn't you think of that in the beginning, because it was only three days. I don't know what will happen after the whole process. We may be able to do this until the epidemic is almost over, but if all of this has abated, then our mission has been fulfilled.

(as far as the information on this platform is concerned,) there is basically no big gap in the city of Wuhan now, and all 7788s have been alleviated. There are some very urgent needs that the hospital will talk to us about. In addition, even if the hospital is no longer officially issued, but the Department of medical care if the lack of it, it will be issued. But in this case, we see very little of it. Other county-level gaps are relatively large,

One of the current priorities is to re-approve the verified information, with a possible later focus on county hospitals, where priority needs will be placed.

I also saw Sichuan, Chongqing, Guangdong, also came out a few requests for assistance information. We are prepared to do it step by step, but also step by step to iteration. When this is done, we'll look at the national situation. Depends on how the outbreak progresses. People have needs, and if we can make a difference, we'll meet that need.

Before that, when I felt like the outbreak was going on and nobody was in charge, I got a little bit angry. But after I made this platform, I became more rational, because I would receive some information from the government or the media. They were actually doing something, just saying they had their own process, some of the procedures are so cumbersome that they do not allow for quick decisions to be made outside of national regulations. This specific I am not very convenient to disclose, just a subjective feeling of my own.

After all, we don't have any baggage inside, so we can move quickly. My side of the word is connected to the hospital, volunteers, and civil some of the situation. I find that people still need a little bit of information symmetry. People may have more confidence in the government, and I've become a little more rational myself. I'm happy to do it, myself included. I don't even go to work at night until three or four o'clock here has been developed online, the whole person is full of energy.
